Q5:
The correlation is not equal to the sum of the products of the z-scores. After you have computed the z-scores for each data point, 
use the CORREL function. The CORREL function takes two arguments, array1, array2. array1 is all z-scores for the X data set, array2 
is the z-scores for the Y data set.
Tip: To calculate the Z-score, instead of using the formula (xi-mean)/sigma, you can use Excel's STANDARDIZE function.

Question 6
Standardization: (x - average)/std. deviation
All other numbers can be found with Excel formula.

Comments:
Alpha is the y-intercept of the best fit line. It is not explained in great details in the lecture video, but it can be easily computed
if the slope and one point on the line is known. Or, if you have two sets of data points, plot a trend-line and Excel will display 
the equation of the linear model in the form y=beta*x+alpha.

For standardized data, alpha is 0 and the linear model becomes y=beta*x. The video mentioned it briefly. But you can experiment that 
yourself. If you have two sets of data, standardize them, then plot the z-scores on a XY-plane, the trend-line (or the best fit line)
runs through the origin.

Beta is the slope of the best fit line. No further explanation is needed.

R is the correlation coefficient. Usually, the correlation coefficient is given by Covariance(X,Y) / sigma(x)*sigma(y). Sigma is the 
standard deviation. However, for standardized data, R=Covariance=Beta. The instructor briefly mentioned the proof. I worked out the 
somewhat complicated details and present them below for those who are interested.

Standardized values are the z-scores. Covariance of standized values is Division by n, since this is a population covariance. 
For z-scores are standardized data, Âµx = 0 = Âµy . The above formula is reduced to

The correlation coefficient of the z-scores is therefore

Since the data points are standardized values, Î´_ð‘§ð‘¥ =1=Î´_ð‘§ð‘¦The correlation coefficient formula thus is reduced back to the covariance
formula. Hence, for standardized values, covariance=R
To prove the equality with beta, the mean squared errors of a best fit line is

Consider Î² as an unknow variable and differentiate the above function.This involes using the power rule and chain rule of 
differentiation. I will ommit the details here, since this is not a calculus class. After applying first the power rule, then
the chain rule, then simplification, the derivative is

Set the derivative to 0 and solve for Î².

Taking into consideration that the data are standardized and the standard deviation of standard normal distribution is 1
Substitute this observation back to the expression for Î² and put the summation sign back

This is exactly the formula for covariance for the standardized values.Hence, we prove that for standardized values 
(the z-scores), Î²=R=Covariance

